title: THE MANY SAINTS OF NEWARK ‚Äì Official Trailer
description:
Legends aren‚Äôt born. They‚Äôre made. A prequel to The Sopranos, watch the new trailer for #TheManySaintsOfNewark, in theaters and streaming exclusively on HBO Max* October 1.
 
*Only available on the Ad-Free plan. Available for 31 days from theatrical release. Films and release dates subject to change.
 
https://www.facebook.com/newarkmovie 
https://twitter.com/NewarkMovie 
https://www.instagram.com/newarkmovie
https://www.themanysaintsofnewarkmovie.com
 
New Line Cinema‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Many Saints of Newark‚Äù is the much-anticipated feature film prequel to David Chase‚Äôs groundbreaking, award-winning HBO drama series ‚ÄúThe Sopranos.‚Äù
 
Young Anthony Soprano is growing up in one of the most tumultuous eras in Newark‚Äôs history, becoming a man just as rival gangsters begin to rise up and challenge the all-powerful DiMeo crime family‚Äôs hold over the increasingly race-torn city. Caught up in the changing times is the uncle he idolizes, Dickie Moltisanti, who struggles to manage both his professional and personal responsibilities‚Äîand whose influence over his nephew will help make the impressionable teenager into the all-powerful mob boss we‚Äôll later come to know: Tony Soprano.
 
‚ÄúThe Many Saints of Newark‚Äù stars Alessandro Nivola (‚ÄúDisobedience,‚Äù ‚ÄúAmerican Hustle‚Äù), Tony winner Leslie Odom Jr. (Broadway‚Äôs ‚ÄúHamilton,‚Äù ‚ÄúMurder on the Orient Express‚Äù), Jon Bernthal (‚ÄúBaby Driver,‚Äù ‚ÄúThe Wolf of Wall Street‚Äù), Corey Stoll (‚ÄúFirst Man,‚Äù ‚ÄúAnt-Man‚Äù), Michael Gandolfini (TV‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Deuce‚Äù), Billy Magnussen (‚ÄúGame Night,‚Äù ‚ÄúThe Big Short‚Äù), Michela De Rossi (‚ÄúBoys Cry,‚Äù TV‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe Rats‚Äù), John Magaro (‚ÄúThe Finest Hours,‚Äù ‚ÄúNot Fade Away‚Äù), with Emmy winner Ray Liotta (TV‚Äôs ‚ÄúShades of Blue,‚Äù ‚ÄúGoodfellas‚Äù) and Oscar nominee Vera Farmiga (‚ÄúUp in the Air,‚Äù ‚ÄúThe Conjuring‚Äù films).
 
Alan Taylor (‚ÄúThor: The Dark World‚Äù), who won an Emmy for his directing work on ‚ÄúThe Sopranos,‚Äù is helming the film from a screenplay by series creator David Chase & Lawrence Konner, based on characters created by Chase.  Chase, Konner and Nicole Lambert are producing the film, with Michael Disco, Marcus Viscidi, Toby Emmerich and Richard Brener serving as executive producers.
 
Taylor‚Äôs behind-the-scenes creative team includes director of photography Kramer Morgenthau (‚ÄúCreed II,‚Äù ‚ÄúThor: The Dark World‚Äù), production designer Bob Shaw (‚ÄúThe Wolf of Wall Street,‚Äù ‚ÄúThe Sopranos‚Äù), Oscar-nominated editor Christopher Tellefsen (‚ÄúMoneyball,‚Äù ‚ÄúA Quiet Place‚Äù) and costume designer Amy Westcott (‚ÄúThe Wrestler,‚Äù ‚ÄúBlack Swan‚Äù).
 
‚ÄúThe Many Saints of Newark‚Äù was shot on location in New Jersey and New York, and several beloved characters from the original series that inspired the film are featured in the movie. During its six-season run, ‚ÄúThe Sopranos‚Äù‚Äîwidely regarded as one of the greatest and most influential television drama series of all time‚Äîwas honored with 21 Primetime Emmy Awards, five Golden Globe Awards, and two Peabody Awards, to name only a portion.
 
New Line Cinema Presents, In Association with Home Box Office, a Chase Films Production, ‚ÄúThe Many Saints of Newark.‚Äù The film is slated for release in theaters nationwide on October 1, 2021 and will be available in the U.S. on HBO Max for 31 days from theatrical release. It is being distributed worldwide by Warner Bros. Pictures and has been rated R for strong violence, pervasive language, sexual content and some nudity.

title: when you hire a real criminal to act
description:
Known to most as Paulie ‚ÄúWalnuts‚Äù Gualtieri ‚Äì Tony Sirico helped Sopranos change the landscape of modern television. 

But what some may not know is that Tony Sirico‚Äôs background is closely similar to his portrayed character. Before Sopranos Sirico was a gangster associated with the Colombo family. In this video we dive deeper into Sirico‚Äôs past and how it influenced his appearances in Sopranos, Goodfellas, Miami Vice and Godfather 2.

Rarely does food play such a central character in a TV show or movie that's not specifically about food, but in The Sopranos, it might as well be one of the family. title: The Most Devastating Deaths On The Sopranos
description:
Hailed as one of the greatest television shows of all time, The Sopranos spent six seasons delving into the world of organized crime in New Jersey. The series launched the careers of a number of actors and not only put HBO on the map, but proved that television could truly compete with film as an artistic medium.
Violence on the show wasn‚Äôt pretty, and no one was safe from it. And as we all know, TV greatness can never be achieved without the death of at least a few characters we know and love ‚Äî or love to hate. Let's take a look at the most devastating deaths on The Sopranos.

title: The Sopranos || Wonderful Life
description:
WATCH IN 1080HD + HEADPHONES 

WARNINGS: Violence, disturbing images and SPOILERS to the whole show.

"They say that sometimes we go around feeling pity for ourselves. But behind our back a great wind is carrying us".

I finished watching this wonderful show last night, and my god, I already miss it. Truly a magnificent show, it became one of my favorites so quickly. 
Tony Soprano is my favorite character from the show, and Chrissy is right after him, so it's pretty obvious why I used so many scenes of these two.

I orignally started working on this project when I first started the show, back then I still used Sony Vegas, but then I decided to take a break from the video for a few seasons, but around season 4 I got back to it again, and I edited this while I was watching. I believe my next Sopranos video will be a bit better than this one.

If you still haven't watched this AMAZING show, I highly recommend you to start right now aha

title: FURIO WAS THE ONLY ITALIAN #sopranos #shorts
description:
NEW TONY SOPRANO Funko Pop! - https://amzn.to/3GdST1u

"Christopher" is the 42nd episode of the HBO original series The Sopranos and the third episode of the show's fourth season. It's teleplay was written by Michael Imperioli, from a story idea by Imperioli and Maria Laurino. It was directed by Tim Van Patten and originally aired on September 29, 2002.

Silvio wants to take action against Native Americans protesting the Columbus Day parade, believing their actions to be insulting to Italian-Americans. When, without Tony's approval, he, Patsy, and Artie attempt to break up the protest, Little Paulie and several others are injured. Ralphie threatens the protest leader, Professor Del Redclay, that he will make it known that Iron Eyes Cody, a popular Native American figure, was actually an Italian-American. Tony unsuccessfully appeals to Assemblyman Ron Zellman and to an Indian chief to convince Redclay to cancel the protest. The chief invites Tony and his crew to his casino. Both the parade and protest occur without mob intervention, which upsets Silvio. Tony forcefully argues to Silvio that his achievements came through his own abilities, not through his heritage, and scorns the idea that everyone belongs to a victimized group.

title: THE SOPRANOS Full Series Recap | Season 1-6 Ending Explained
description:
Relive the entire series of The Sopranos now! Seasons 1-6!

Buy merch: https://recap-chill-shop.fourthwall.com/

Primarily set in New Jersey and New York City, the series follows Tony Soprano, a North Jersey-based Italian-American mobster, who tries to balance his family life with his role as boss of the Soprano family. Suffering from panic attacks, Tony engages in therapy sessions with psychiatrist Jennifer Melfi off and on throughout the series. At various points in the series, Tony finds himself at odds with his uncle Junior, his wife Carmela, other mobsters within the Soprano family, and the New York City-based Lupertazzi family, putting his life at risk on multiple occasions.

The Sopranos stars James Gandolfini as Tony Soprano, Lorraine Bracco as Dr. Jennifer Melfi, Edie Falco as Carmela Soprano, Michael Imperioli as Christopher Moltisanti, Vincent Pastore as Salvatore "Big Pussy" Bonpensiero, Steven Van Zandt as Silvio Dante, Tony Sirico as Paulie "Walnuts" Gaultieri, Robert Iler as Anthony "AJ" Soprano Jr., Jamie Lynn-Sigler as Meadow Soprano, Dominic Chianese as Corrado "Junior" Soprano, Nancy Marchand as Livia Soprano, Drea de Mateo as Adriana, David Proval as Richie Aprile, Aida Turturro as Janice, John Ventimiglia as Artie Bucco, Federico Castelluccio as Furio, Steven Schirripa as Bobby Baccala, Joe Pantoliano as Ralph Cifaretto, Vincent Curatola as Johnny Sack, Steve Buscemi as Tony B, Joseph R. Gannascoli as Vito Spatafore, Dan Grimaldi as Patsy Parisi, Frank Vincent as Phil Leotardo.

This is a recap of some of the biggest and best moments from the entire Sopranos series, including The Sopranos season 1-6. This video includes massive spoilers for the series finale ending and more!

title: Why You're Wrong About Bobby Bacala | The Sopranos
description:
SUPPORT THE CHANNEL ON PATREON: https://www.patreon.com/user?u=8580945

FOLLOW ME ON TWITTER: https://twitter.com/CineRanter

FOLLOW ME ON INSTAGRAM: https://www.instagram.com/cineranter1/

FOLLOW ME ON TIKTOK: https://www.tiktok.com/@cineranter?

HBO‚Äôs The Sopranos follows the trials and tribulations of New Jersey mob boss Tony Soprano. The show contains a wide variety of interesting characters with depth and nuance, from Christopher Moltisanti, Janice Soprano, Ritchie April, Ralph Cifaretto,  Johnny Sack and much much more.

Many of the supporting characters of the shows are now legendary and iconic, and there is perhaps no character more beloved to Sopranos fans than Bobby Baccalieri, better known as Bobby Bacala, played by Steve Schiripa. First appearing in ‚ÄòDo Not Resuscitate‚Äô, the 2nd episode of the second season of the show, Bobby has gone onto become perhaps the most loved character in the entire series. He‚Äôs a big guy, but he‚Äôs got a big heart, he‚Äôs shy, na√Øve, and thoughtful. He‚Äôs a little dub, which makes him endearing, and he gets made fun of a lot in the show and is something of a pushover. He also formed a dynamic duo with Junior Soprano, the two characters sharing excellent chemistry and playing off one another in entertaining fashion. This ‚Äúaw shucks‚Äù attitude of the character sticks out in a bizarre way but lovable way, given how Bobby is surrounded by vicious sociopaths and bloodthirsty killers. This gentle giant has won the hearts of Sopranos fans everywhere, with notable reasons being his love for his children and his faithfulness to his wife Karen, the fact that he as a grown man in the mob played with trains, and his tragic death, which came via a mob execution as part of a mob war which Bobby thought was over, but he had been misinformed. Bobby is remembered by fans of the show as a lovable big goof, the only decent guy out of the main characters in the show, one who only truly became unshakably angry when the lives of his children were in danger.  

Today however, I wanted to offer an alternate take, one that will perhaps be controversial for Sopranos fans.

The Sopranos  S1E4
In the fourth episode of the first season of "The Sopranos", Tony encounters a problem when dealing with gang affairs: the old-fashioned gang member Herman refuses to cooperate in collecting protection money and even colludes with others to resist Tony's arrangement. Tony has no choice but to apply both soft and hard pressure. Meanwhile, his psychotherapy was still ongoing. Jennifer guided him to face up to his complex emotions towards his father - both admiring his authority and being dissatisfied with his neglect of the family. In terms of family, Camilla discovered that Tony had secretly given money to his mother, Livia. The two had an argument because of Livia's "double-sided behavior". Medeline turned to Tony for help with her dance partner at the school dance. title: The First and Last Lines Spoken by The Sopranos Characters (130+ characters, pt. 1 & 2 complete)
description:
Methodology:

1. I focused on characters that made 3-or-more episode appearances. Some characters included only made 2. A handful that made 3 were not included. Kids were not included. I included George Pagileri, a single episode character, at the end because it made for a better finale.

2. I focused on first and last lines, not scenes. Tony Blundetto doesn‚Äôt say anything before Tony Soprano shoots him so that is not his ‚Äúlast line.‚Äù

3. I considered a line to be any word of spoken dialogue that was probably written as dialogue (as opposed to being written as an action line, in terms of the teleplay). For this reason, Tony‚Äôs initial ‚Äúyeah‚Äù and Meadow‚Äôs final ‚Äúshit‚Äù were included. However, the struggling noises that Eugene makes when he is hanging is probably written as an action line. Similarly, Jason Gervasi‚Äôs ‚Äúalright‚Äù in ‚ÄúChasing it‚Äù happens technically before the ‚Äúenvelopes‚Äù line to Tony in the video but it didn‚Äôt appear to be written specifically as dialogue to me. Similarly, Beansie, greets a customer before the line included in the vid but again, appeared incidental. I did though consider Paulie‚Äôs ‚ÄúOoo‚Äù to be written specific to his character which is why that was included. One final example is even though Rhiannon Flamer is seen laughing, watching TV with AJ after the line included in the video, I again considered that that was probably written as ‚ÄúRhiannon laughs‚Äù and not ‚ÄúRHIANNON: Hahahah‚Äù. In general, I used my own discretion.

4. I opted to include the two different actors in the pilot who played Father Phil and Irina but did not do this for any other actor changes throughout the series, for example, Joanne Moltisanti, Quintina Blundetto etc.

5. Adrian La Cerva was retroactively determined to be ‚ÄúAdrianna‚Äù in the pilot by the writers after it aired. I believe Chris‚Äôs line, heard in the video as Adrianna answers the door, is meant to allude to this and she is also listed in the credits as such. I‚Äôve included both scenes though.

6. Anthony Infante technically says the ‚Äúcheers‚Äù line with Bing guys after the ‚Äúfor the best‚Äù line included in the vid but since it was a group saying it together and for timing, I didn‚Äôt include it.

7. It‚Äôs possible Tom Giglione says an ADR/off-screen line after the ‚ÄúYeats‚Äù line included in the vid, but I prefer the Yeats line in any case.

8. You could say Furio‚Äôs last line was the answering machine message when Carmela calls him but I didn‚Äôt consider that to be the case.

9. I didn‚Äôt consider Flashbacks or Dreams when it comes to ‚Äúfirst lines‚Äù or "last lines", in other words, Jackie Aprile Sr, Livia Soprano, Corrado Soprano Jr., and others, first lines are when they are heard within the general timeframe of the show and not during flashbacks. 

10. Technically, Billy Leotardo‚Äôs last line is delivered via Flashback from Phil Leotardo but since it was within the general timeframe of the show I‚Äôve included it.

11. You could argue that Vito‚Äôs last line is when he is in the car talking to Tony but I distinctly hear a ‚Äúno‚Äù, although come to think of it that was probably written as an action line in the script, oh well, it‚Äôs staying.

12. I did not include the Olivia Soprano CGI scene, and I don‚Äôt think Chase should have either.

title: The Miserable Waiter Became Chris & Paulie's Punching Bag#viral #shorts #tvshow #thesopranos #movie
description:
In the first episode of the fifth season of "The Sopranos", Tony wakes up from a coma. His body and memory have not yet fully recovered, and he feels strange about his surroundings. Camilla takes good care of him by his side but can't hide her worry. Meanwhile, the gang was leaderless. Paul ie and Cillian were engaged in a covert struggle for temporary control, and business disputes followed one after another. Christopher tried to steady the situation but was unable to do so. In addition, Tony's dreams frequently feature symbolic signs, reflecting his confusion about power and self. This episode takes Tony's difficult recovery as the thread, interwoven with the dual turmoil of his family and gang.

title: Tony Sent the Elderly Mafia Member to Prison#shorts #viral #thesopranos #youtubeshorts #clips#fyp#tv
description:
The Sopranos S5E4
In the fourth episode of the fifth season of "The Sopranos", the power struggle between Johnny Sacker and Camain Jr. escalates. Lorraine and Jason are executed by Phil. Milo urges Camain Jr. to confront him head-on, while Angelo urges him to be patient. In New Jersey, Mitchel, a veteran gang member who has just been released from prison, disregarded Tony's authority. Not only did he fob off the casino management work he arranged, but he also sold the stolen luxury car to Johnny instead of his own gang. Tony didn't want to repeat Richie's mistake and ingeniously set up a trap to make Mitchel violate the parole regulations and return to prison. At the same time, Camilla confessed to the school advisor that she was extremely worried that her son Anthony would fail to get into college and follow in Tony's footsteps, and she was filled with fear.

#thesopranos #shorts #youtubeshorts #carimedrama #sopranos #trendingshorts  #shorts #vrial #viralvideo  #watchnow  #bingewatch  #mustwatch  #thesopranos2025 #clips #tv #fyp
In the 11th episode of the 5th season of "The Sopranos", Tony is under double pressure: on the one hand, the New York gang forces are trying to interfere in the garbage disposal business in New Jersey, and he needs to negotiate hard to hold his ground. However, due to his deputy Bobby's lack of experience, the negotiation process often gets stuck. On the other hand, his daughter Medeline was embroiled in an alcohol scandal at college. Tony wanted to settle it with money, but was opposed by his wife Camilla, and a fierce argument broke out between the couple. Meanwhile, Christopher lost control again due to the drug problem and almost leaked the gang's secrets. Although Tony, out of consideration for the past, did not punish him severely, he secretly weakened his power. At the end of this episode, Tony smokes alone in the office. Facing the crisis of the family business and the rift in family relations, it fully reveals the loneliness and powerlessness of the gang boss, laying the groundwork for the subsequent conflict. #besttvshow#crimedrama

The Sopranos ending explained. Who killed Tony Soprano? Who shot Tony Soprano? What happened at the end of The Sopranos? Did Tony Soprano die? 

In the final scene of The Sopranos, Tony arrives at Holsteins for a mean with his family, and selects Journey‚Äôs Don‚Äôt Stop Believing from the joke box console at his table. One after the other, Carmella and AJ arrive, with Meadow outside struggling to park her car. They eat, engage in small talk, and just as Meadow reaches the diner door, Tony looks up, and we cut to black. And so ends one of the most infamous endings to any TV show, one that has infuriated fans, leading many to think something was wrong with their TV when they first watched it. It is a hotly debated topic, even today decades later, as to what actually happened, with many fans thinking Tony was shot dead in that moment.

In this video, I wanted to explore the possibility of Tony having died, and in particular, running down a list of suspects of who could have wanted him dead and carrying it out.

In HBO‚Äôs classic mob drama The Sopranos, we follow New Jersey mob boss Tony Soprano and his attempt to survive the treacherous world of the mafia, the long arm of the law, and the headache-inducing world of family life.

In the series‚Äô final episode, ‚ÄúMade in America‚Äù, a sit down is arranged between Tony and Paulie, representing the DiMeos, and Butch and Albie Cianfalone, representing the Lupertazzis. Butch expresses his dissatisfaction with Phil‚Äôs leadership and agrees to a ceasefire. He does not reveal Phil‚Äôs location, but agrees not to get in the way, and eventually, Phil is shot and killed at a gas station in front of his wife and grandchildren, and his head is crushed by his own SUV for good measure.

The war is over, and presumably, Butch takes Phil‚Äôs seat as boss of the family.

But a question does arise here ‚Äì why did Butch turn on Phil so suddenly?

title: Bobby Earned Seven Thousand Dollars for Tony#thesopranos #shorts #youtubeshorts #crimedrama
description:
The Sopranos S6E4
#thesopranos #shorts #youtubeshorts #carimedrama #sopranos  
The Sopranos Season 6, Episode 4 hides the cruelty of the "mafia" in the trivialities of daily life, laying out crises with almost plain shots. Tony seems to handle family affairs as usual, but his quarrels with his men and calculations about business are all hidden beneath the dialogue. There are no intense conflicts, yet everywhere there is an oppression of loosening power.
Carmela's struggle between family and morality is more realistic. Her avoidance of Tony's career and the violence she accidentally witnesses form a disconnect, grounding the character's sense of contradiction. This episode does not rely on a strong plot, but accumulates tension through life fragments - the silence over a glass of wine, averted eyes for a moment - all hinting at the coming storm, which accurately fits the show's unique style of "deconstructing the mafia through daily life".

Later, when Tony and Johnny Saccgolf learned that there was a witness of the lame murderer at the scene of Joe Pippes' death. He questioned Bredeto but was denied. Feeling guilty about Bredeto's imprisonment, Tony chose to keep it a secret and gave him the management rights of the casino, which aroused Christopher's dissatisfaction. Meanwhile, Camilla initiated the divorce process, but due to Tony's influence, she couldn't find a lawyer willing to take over or an accountant daring to investigate her finances. title: Mustang Sally Got Clipped. ü•ä #TheSopranos #Shorts
Christopher Stopped Anthony from Avenging His Father#shorts #thesopranos #vrial #tv#clips #movie#fyp
description:
The Sopranos S6E1~S6E3
With suppression as the shell and cracks as the core - the cold and stern metaphor of the revenge scene in "The Sophors" S6. After Tony is attacked by his uncle, his son Anthony's urge for revenge is forcibly suppressed. This scene tears off the warm mask of the gangster family. Anthony's anger was originally a blood instinct, but it was suppressed by Tony with the idea of "considering the overall situation" - seemingly a father protecting his son and maintaining stability, but in fact, it exposed the instrumental nature of family ties in the gangster world: when emotions threaten the power order, even the most natural blood ties have to give way to the calculation of interests. Tony's intervention failed to resolve the conflict; instead, it only deepened the rift. It implies that the trust within the family has collapsed and also sets the stage for the turmoil in the power structure in the subsequent plot, which is chilling and terrifying.

title: Why You're Wrong About Phil Leotardo | The Sopranos
description:
In The Sopranos, Phil Leotardo - played by Frank Vincent - becomes boss of the New York Lupertazzi family. Many Sopranos fans consider Phil to be an annoying character who is too emotional to be a mob boss and is always talking about how he did 20 years in prison. 

But in today's video, I wanted to offer a case for Phil Leotardo, to offer an analysis of Phil Leotardo and show he is a lot more complex and nuanced than people give him credit for.

title: The Sopranos Season Two Tier List | Ranked and Reviewed
description:
After many, many months, we are FINALLY back to cover season two of The Sopranos! Lots of fans of the show consider this season to be one of the show's strongest, containing some of The Soprano's most legendary moments. But is this actually a fact or merely a remnant of Tony's garbage routes? There's only one way to find out, and that's by watching, reviewing, and ranking every episode of the season on a TIER LIST! If any of my opinions make you extremely angry, let me know in the comments section below! Thank you all very much for your patience, and I hope YOU (yes, YOU!) enjoy this video. Take care!

title: The Sopranos | Why You're Wrong About Tony Blundetto
description:
Tony Blundetto is a major character on The Sopranos. He is Tony Soprano's maternal cousin who served 16 years in prison on hijacking charges before being released in 2004 and trying to go legitimate and starting a career as a massage therapist, but finds himself returning back to his life of crime, leading him into a spiral of destruction that damages the Soprano family's business relationship with the Lupertazzi family. Eventually, Tony B is taken out by Tony Soprano. He is portrayed by Steve Buscemi.

In today's video, I want to make the controversial argument that Tony Blundetto is actually a poorly written and poorly acted character. In fact, from the main cast of The Sopranos, Tony B is the worst character in the show.

The Lupertazzi Family
A major New York crime family, wealthier, larger, and more politically connected. They‚Äôre portrayed as more ‚Äúcorporate‚Äù and structured, with layers of leadership and business interests that extend far beyond the street-level rackets. Their internal politics, however, are often brutal and treacherous.

The Soprano Family (DiMeo Family)
A smaller New Jersey crew with less influence and fewer resources. Tony‚Äôs crew is more personal, volatile, and tightly knit, with conflicts that arise from loyalty issues, family dynamics, and Tony‚Äôs own leadership style. They often feel overshadowed by New York and rely on negotiating power rather than dominance.

Benny Fazio is a low-level soldier in the DiMeo crime family on *The Sopranos*, portrayed by Max Casella. He starts out as an associate working under Christopher Moltisanti and later becomes a made man. Benny is loyal but hot-headed, often getting caught up in petty feuds and violent errands. He represents the younger, street-level side of the mob, ambitious, reckless, and eager to prove himself.
